column1: the concepts in the question are too vague to be meaningful
Really? Why are you asking me a maths question??!!
My 90% confidence interval is 1500 to 15000. I am not convinced the "best" charities are orders of magnitude different from average ones once you are in the same cause area.
Do you mean the highest actual level of a currently existing charity? If so I guess $100,000 or more.

It's not clear to me if "average" means mean or median; for all I know, both the mean and the median impact of these charities might be negative, so it's not clear to me how I'm supposed to reply. My first thought, which I think was generated by asking myself how much worse the median charity is while assuming it still has positive impact, was "1,000,000 $" (1 million), but this estimate is quite unstable and not something I'd endorse without thinking more about this.
What do my feelings have to do with evidence-based giving? Sorry, but I think I'll opt out of the rest of the survey (I've had a tough day at work!)
What percentage is the Highest Level of Effectiveness? 70%, 80%, 95%?
Not possible to answer given lack of detail in question
I'm assuming 'average level' to be 0.5 x the cost-effectiveness of Charity A. Therefore B would need $2000.
There isnt enough information to answer the question
I find this criterion far too simplistic, and do not choose to make guesses based upon it.
Not enough info to answer - highest might only mean slightly higher than average.
Can't answer without knowing what 'highest' and 'average' mean.
2000 (you haven't specified how much more effective Charity A is, so I'm assuming twice)
170 but I'd rather have a centrally organised charity than multiple smaller ones for efficiency reasons

1,000.  I don't believe that how many lives you save should be a measure of cost effectiveness.  The poorest people need more than a beating heart.  They need education, shelter, medical aid and employment
how Can I answer this with the limited data provided?
Not enough info provided. It depends on the difference in lives saved per $ between the average and best charities.
More than 1k clearly.  my guess would be 1.2k
Sorry to be difficult, but mean/median are really different here. Mean: $50000, Median: $100000
Not clear what this Q is getting at, but it strays from the data-driven backbone of EA

I am a bit skeptic to the argument that EA-related charities are up to 100 times more effective than the average charity (see Tomasik article Why Charities Usually Don't Differ Astronomically in Expected Cost-Effectiveness) and I do not think that probing my knowledge with this question promotes a nuanced vision of EA. :)
Isn't the point of EA not to guess? I'd probably go by givewells recommendations. I imagine that the average charity is quite lower than AMF, deworm the world, or givedirectly.
are you just asking what average means?
There's no need to make a best guess - just need to know how much money it costs to "save a life."
this question is vague and probably should be scrapped
No amount of money is sufficient on its own
Assuming both's ONLY goale is to postpone death's of people in the actual situation of facing death (not preventing risks of death, or alliviate the burden of deseases and so on), I'd guess $1200.

I think this would fluctuate between causes (where from what I have seen, more cost-effective animal charities (e.g. MFA) seem to be relatively more cost-effective than top-tier human development charities (e.g. AMF)), but assuming that "lives" are human in this instance, then I would guess $40,000

I think this question is too vague to answer. In what sense is B 'average'? Is it just averaged over all individual charities in a given reference class, or is it weighted by how much money they spend? Do I include only charities that actually help the world's poorest people, or do I include charities that purport to help the poor in general?
I weakly lean towards thinking that the averagely cost-effective charity actually has a negative impact (due to poor meat-eater problems and such), so I guess my answer is: infinity
Difference would be likely in orders of magnitude, 100 000$ or more
this seems to be asking how many times more effective the most cost effective charity for global poverty is compared to the average.  I do not have enough data to make an accurate prediction.
$1000 is too small to expect it to have saved a life
I don't have any idea what 'average' might be
That depends a lot on how you compute your average
